segments.text: I didn't, you know, because I thought, you know, by God, if you're going to do this, you've got to do it yourself.
And it's a sign of weakness and inability if you go so silly.
So, in fact, that was an issue when my junior year came around and I needed teacher recommendations and I didn't know who I would go ask.
As far as you and your friends were aware, were there any easy courses, giveaway grades,
Cowboy chemistry was a giveaway grade.
That was for ag majors?
Yeah, yeah.
But not really.
Were there any that you heard of where the athletes got freebies?
Yeah, but not freebies, but just the ones that they all took.
There was a, what was it, the marriage and family class.
Dr. Dan, the grade player.
Yeah.
Dan Russell.
And I heard that the football players all took that one.

But everybody wanted to take that one because, you know, they saw, you know, Grody films and, you know, did stuff that everybody wanted to talk about that our society still wasn't too clear it wanted to have out in the open.
I never took it.
One of my buddies did.
It was an education major.
Who were some of the celebrity students that were here, the students that were high profile?
Fred McClure.
Did you meet Fred?
We were very dear friends.
We worked in student government together.
Make believe I'd never met him.
Okay.
Describe it.
It was, and I don't even remember Fred much from my freshman year, but Fred was elected speaker of the student senate my sophomore year, and I was recording secretary.
I'd gone from being an executive aide to being recording secretary my sophomore year, so we ran the student senate meetings every couple of weeks, and so that's how Fred, and Fred
And I remember just being incredibly impressed that here was a black man who had been president of the National FFA.
And that just blew me away right there.
I thought, this guy has got to be incredible.
To be, you know, in the mid-70s, you know, a black president of what was perceived then to be a pretty redneck organization, right?
I thought, man, this guy's got to be incredible, and sure enough, he was.
He was so full of life, so much fun, so bright.
He still... And I have been doing...

I'm speaker myself and have been doing stuff in the AMA and the TMA, parliamentary stuff for years, and I have never seen anybody with a mastery of parliamentary procedure like Fred McClure did when he was a junior in college.
It just blew me away.
We had so much fun.
And...
Fred McClure was larger than life.
Tony Franklin was larger than life.
Everybody knew who Tony Franklin was.
And I remember running into him one time, and my asthma had flared up, and I was getting checked out in the student center, and Tony Franklin evidently just owned the place.
He could just go anywhere he wanted to, and Tony Franklin walks in the room while the doctor's checking me out.
Unfortunately, I was dressed, but I just remember thinking, oh, my God, you know, here's this football hero standing right here, and everybody knew him, and
But the football players were Lester Hayes and Pat Thomas and all those guys were heroes.
Where's their?
Was there yet a highly visible, prominent co-ed student?
Yes, Kim Tomes, who won Miss USA.
That's T-O-M-E-S.
Yes, yes, Kim Tomes won Miss USA, and she lived in Kruger with us, and I'll never forget, because, you know, we talked about the dorm dress code.
Well, Kim would go down to eat breakfast in a T-shirt and jeans and no makeup and just like anybody else.
But when she went into pageant mode, oh, my goodness, just a total knockout.
And so much fun and so down to earth.
She was a blast.
And we were all so proud because we really, the women on campus,
Really, her winning Miss USA and being an Aggie was incredibly inspirational to us.
It made us feel really good about having arrived.
And the jokes about women at A&M being less than gorgeous or whatever.
And so that was, yeah, Kim was probably the highest profile female that I remember.
MSC, what role did the MSC play then in student?
It was very big.
Of course, they didn't have near the number of organizations that they did now, but at least it seemed very big to me because I was active in organizations on campus.
So that's where, you know, the kids that were interested and active, whether you were in the Corps or not,
male or female, they were involved in MSC activities.

They were in student government, they were in SCONA, they were on OPUS, they were in Town Hall, they were, those were the kids that were, enjoyed other people, wanted to be involved, wanted to do something, wanted to be a part of something.
It was very, very important.
Did you meet Wayne Stark?
Yes.
Just make believe I didn't know him.
Describe him.
Wayne, Mr. Stark, was, I was very intimidated by him at first because he was obviously the kingpin of the MSC, really ran a fairly tight ship.
You know, you could tell which kids he favored and which kids really didn't know him very well.

And what I did not realize until I really got to know him later on, probably my junior year, I guess, was how, what a mother hen he really was and how he loved those students and what incredible pride he took in their achievements after they left A&M.
And because when Wayne Stark became your advocate, it was like you had General Patton out there fighting for you.
He was just amazing.
And it was so fun to visit with him in later years, either while I was in medical school or whatever, brag about him.
kids that had done this and that, kids that you didn't even realize he had known.
And so that was having his presence.
Some students, the people that work with the students closely in student organization type stuff, sometimes there's kind of a buddy mentality or there's a grandfather mentality.
And he was definitely the grandfather type.
And
And he was just delightful.
Did you ever hear anybody talk about getting the green couch treatment from him?
Vaguely, but I don't remember.
He had this old, old crotchety looking
green formaldehyde-covered couch, and if he felt that you were goofing off and not living up to your potential, he would maneuver you, close the door, and there was a lecture that you never forgot.
It was called the green couch treatment.
It had nothing to do with sex.
No, no.
It was to...
Oh, that's funny.
Let's see.
Was Chad Edwards around?
Yes.
Well, no.
He had just graduated.
Had he?
Okay.
Every once in a while, he would come to the student government office, and I'd see him there, but I really didn't.
I just knew who he was, and I knew that all the girls in the student government adored him.
And he was quite a presence even then.
Of course, he was handsome.
He was charismatic.
He was bright.
He obviously had an incredible future ahead.
And like...
a number of successful politicians just have this charisma about them that draws you to them.
Let's see.
And so the MSC was a valuable, valuable... Oh, yes.
Incredible.
Was the Rudder Center finished?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, it was finished.
Do you remember any important events there?
see or hear any great concerts or speakers that were?
I remember Vladimir Horowitz played.
Okay.
That was pretty amazing.
The first formal concert was Van Cliburn.
Oh my gosh.
That was the first.
I just remember just what a gorgeous facility it was and how impressed I was with the elegance.
With your profession now, did you go to the Quack Shack when you were a student?
Mm-hmm.
Describe it.
Oh, well.

It did not have the best reputation, as many student health centers don't, but I wasn't afraid to go over there because I still had, my asthma still kicked up occasionally and I tended to get sick a lot and for some reason,
Most children get tonsillitis when they're three or four years old.
I didn't start having tonsillitis until I was in college.
And for a while, they got it about once a month.
So I seemed to be over there a lot.
But I just remember...
But the physicians that I talked to seemed to be...
They were okay.
Do you remember any of them by name?
Well, who was the head?
Gos... Yeah.
Goswin?
Goswick?
Something like that.
Yeah, and then later did some work with the medical school, and I just thought he was delightful.
There was one guy there that I, you know, I had a female problem, and he misprescribed it and gave me the wrong medicines, and I was just like, oh, great.
But I'll never forget one time, I guess I was a junior,
and was having a female problem and went over there.
And it was just kind of a, everybody just kind of sat in the lobby together when you were waiting.
And I remember the roommate of the man I eventually married came over and sat down and was like, well, what brings you here to the quack shack?
I have a cold.
Yeah, I have a cold.
And now I'm so glad that women's health services have their own place so that women don't have to be subjected to that kind of embarrassment anymore.
That was mortifying.
So you met a special person here?
In medical school.
In medical school.
Yeah, we didn't know each other's undergraduates.
We'll get there eventually.
What about dates when you were a freshman and sophomore?
I dated some.
Dated some guys in the Corps.

Never thought that that would happen, because I always kind of considered myself fairly liberal-minded, but they were the guys that knew what was going on, they were fun, they had a bunch of buddies, and never missed anything.
They were a lot of fun to be around.
Did they still have the big dances?
Boot dance?
Yeah, I had boot dance, ring dance, yeah.
What was the routine for a young lady at one of those?
Oh, gosh, you sat around and hoped somebody would ask you.
And I remember when one of the seniors did ask me to boot dance when I was a junior.
Oh, my gosh, I just thought that I'd, you know.
How were you all treated at the dance?
Like royalty, like princesses.
That's what everybody has said.
Yes.
Everybody has said.
We were like princesses.
It was incredible.
When, on a big, let's see, they picked you up at the dorm.
Did you all wear formals?
Yes.
Yes, we wore long dresses.
We had corsages.
It was a very...

Well, it was really a very formal process, and the different meaning of the word formal, that they would, you know, be called upstairs, or if they were visiting hours, they would actually come to your room, but more often than not, we'd meet them downstairs in the commons and, you know, get your flower pinned on, and somebody might take a picture, and they'd escort you over to the dance, and it was a very...
And y'all didn't have dance cards.
No, no, no.
And what orchestras?
Because it was a live band, wasn't it?
Usually.
Sometimes, I don't remember.
I don't remember what bands would play.
See, among the things I wish we could resurrect is the Aggieland Orchestra, which did big band music in the 30s and 40s.
They were so successful, they went out of town on buses and made a profit.
Wow.
the Houston, Dallas, Waco, Austin, and they had the, it was Glenn Miller-style music.
Yeah, that'd be wonderful.
We need to have somebody at least play at graduation.
This canned music at graduation thing has got to stop.
I'm with you.
Oh, man.
Back to the dorms.
You all had no male visiting in girls' dorm rooms.
There was.
What were the rules?
The rules?
Well, guys could come in the dorms just during certain hours.

at not during the day on the weekdays as I recall for a few hours in the evening it was okay and on weekends they could come during the day but you know pretty much had to be out of there by midnight or or something like that it was pretty strictly enforced did was there much partying in the dorms oh yeah oh yeah describe what oh it's you know people would get together in somebody's dorm rooms whether it was either just girls or girls and guys and
And there'd be beer, which was legal then, and music and people hollering, and they just had a great time.
And what did you all do if the noise was too much?
What was the system for getting them to tone it down?
I don't remember there ever being an issue.
I don't think anybody cared.
Oh, okay, okay.
If you really needed to study that night, and they're making noise, where did you go?
You went down to the study carrels.
They were very well insulated and quiet.
If the study carrel that you were at was too close to the noise, you could go find another one.
There were plenty of them.
What was the difference between Kruger and Dunn, if any?

Oh, it was done, you know, being the male dorm, it was just a little, yeah, it was just a little, it was a little crazier, but there wasn't much difference between Kruger and Mosier, really, when Mosier came online.
Were there also some women's dorms north campus?
Yes, yeah, Keith Lee Fowler Hughes.
But this was, y'all thought better.
Oh yes, we were cool.
They were just the ordinary people.
What about the food?
The food in the Commons was great.
I think the freshman 15 was probably the freshman 20 or 25 for a lot of us.
Because I remember I was very impressed with, of course you get tired of it after a while, but the quality, the quantity of the food that was served, the
the baked goods were good.
Again, I couldn't believe we had steak night every once in a while and we'd get big old T-bones.
So the food was good.
Alright, let's go back.
Did Mom and Dad give you any advice as you were entering college?
Things to do or not to do?
Not really because, you know, I knew
that there was a standard.
I knew that I was expected to do my best.
I knew that I was expected to not get into trouble.
I knew that I was supposed to be a good girl, and that's just kind of all there was to it.
I mean, there wasn't a sitting down, coming to Jesus meeting about any of that.
And really, about the only advice
This wasn't advice.
Tell me what to do.
Probably sometime, I think it was during my freshman year, there was a place called the Mansard House.
And there were some guys in the corps that were getting up a little band.
And they wanted me to be their accompanist.
And I'd make some money, and they wanted me to go play out there.
And Mother was like, not only no, but hell no.
You know, you don't need to be doing that.
You need to be studying and doing that kind of stuff.
And that was not a debatable?
No, it was not debatable.
Once she gave you that answer.
Yeah, that was not debatable, and I was really mad.
But she was right.
What kind of spending money did you have?
Did you have an allowance or not?
I don't even remember.
I've been trying to think that.
I think I got a monthly allowance, and that was...
That was pretty much it, but I don't remember how much it was.
Not very much, I'm sure.
And you had a telephone in your room.
Yes.
And you made phone calls occasionally home.
Any other phone calls much?
Every once in a while I'd talk to my sister at TCU or talk to friends at other schools.
Is this an older sister?
Yes.
Did you ask her for advice ever?
No.
No.
And when you and, did a group of girls ever go out on a Friday or Saturday?
Oh, yeah.
Where would y'all go?
We would go, we didn't go to the Chicken much.
A lot of people went to the Chicken.
I didn't go there very much.
It was always so crowded and so rowdy.
But the deal was then Thursday nights go to Lakeview.
And so that was the big deal because the beer was 35 cents on Thursday nights and Dennis Ivey and the Wayman would play and there were
the place was packed.
And so that's where people went on Thursday nights.
We'd either get a group of girls going, a group of girls and guys going together.
Sometimes people would have dates, but it was just, that's where everybody went.
And I'll never, and I think my first time at Lakeview made as much of an impression on me as my first Aggie football game.
Because I had really never been around country western dancing, you know, growing up in the middle of Houston.
And
And I will never forget standing in that dance hall and seeing these people, you know, dance country western in this big circle around.
I was just absolutely floored.
Of course, it wasn't too long before I was out there with them and just loved it.
We had so much fun.
So what would y'all wear to Lakeview?
We would wear jeans and boots, but would kind of dress up.
We wanted to look nice.
But we would dance until we were just raining wet.
We danced and we danced and we danced and we danced.
That was okay for a young lady to drink beer?
Yes.
What about something stronger?
That was okay too, but it was awfully expensive.
What were students drinking then?

Oh, silly things like Tom Collins' and rum, you know, bourbon and coke and sweet liquor concoctions, you know, sometimes kind of a, you know, a garbage can, you know, punch type thing with, you know, Everclear and all that, you know, crazy stuff that college kids do.
But it was a, nobody drank wine.
Nobody drank wine.
They drank beer or a sweet mixed drink.
And what were the popular beers?
Oh, Pearl, Schlitz, Lone Star.
There was no Miller Lite.
We didn't have Coors in Texas yet then, so that was a real delicacy if somebody brought some down from Colorado.
Did you or any of your friends ever go to Whiskey Bridge?
No.
But you all knew where it was?
No, I don't even remember that.
You don't?
No.
Oh, straight across, going to Snook, straight across the river on the right was a little of what would have been a convenience store country.
And that, in the olden days, was the nearest place to buy whiskey or to buy anything other than beer.
Okay.
Because this was a dry county.
I do not remember that.
Well, they tore the building down about a year ago as they widened Farm Road 60.
But that was the place you went.
Then one, before you're in my memory,

because i got here in 59 there was a place down about where the copy bridge hamburger place is below 20 on the welborn road there was a place called uncle ed's and his h-y-r-d-l-y-c-k-a herdlicka check but it was hard lickers and you walk down there to drink a lot of beer now you've got an 11 o'clock 11 o'clock okay all right so we'll go and it's here so we're but but where
You say here, where?
In the library?
Yeah, it's in the library someplace, so we don't have to go far.
Let's see.
As a sophomore, was it any different to go to a football game or a basketball game for you?
It was different just because I was more likely to have a date.
I felt more comfortable there.
I felt not as intimidated by...
I knew the traditions.
I felt comfortable with the routine.
All right, let's make believe it's a day game, home game, afternoon.
The date would come pick you up when?
If it was somebody in the Corps, he would come get you before march in.
So it was a couple hours before the game.
All right, and then did you go with him to where?
Well, would follow him as far as we could.
Probably don't go over the quad, you know, where they lined up.
And then they would march in the stadium, and then the girls in their heels and hose and dresses and mums would walk.
We'd all go to the stadium and meet them in the stadium once they got done with marching.
Now, how would you all establish exactly where in the stadium you were going to be while he?
We just had our tickets and met at the seats.
Okay.
Yeah, just met at the seats.
All right.
And there was a mum?
Usually, yeah, usually, yeah, yeah.
And during the game, what kind of shenanigans went on in the stands?
Oh, people just hollered and screamed and had fun.
But not a lot of shenanigans went on in the stands because we watched those yell-eaters and, you know, you obeyed those hand signals.
And it was very much a single-celled organism.
I mean, just the student body just acted as one, as a unit.
Now, in the olden days, it was considered cool for particular sophomore boys to smoke cigars.
Was that, in your day, was that a...
I think there was some of that going on.
I don't remember that much.
Some.
I remember that more at parties than I do at the games.
Did anybody get drunk during the game?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
And what happened to them?
Um... Would sometimes somebody help kind of get them out of the stadium?
Yeah, but I don't remember that happening too much.
I really don't.
Um...
Because everybody knew there was going to be a big party later.
What did a young lady do if the Aggie scored a lot of touchdowns and she had a date with a guy that she really didn't enjoy much?
Well, that's just too bad.
You kissed him anyway.
Or if it was 66 to nothing, perhaps you excused yourself to the restroom and stayed gone as long as you could.
But then he might want to catch up on you when you got back.
Did you go to many out-of-town games?
I went to a few.
I remember coming to the SMU game once for a court trip.
I remember going, yeah, I remember coming back to Houston, I think maybe playing Cougar High in Rice Stadium.
So I went to some of the, never went to Waco, but went to some, never got to go to LSU, never got to do that, because of course, that's a mosquito.
The guys, everybody wanted to go to the LSU game and party on Bourbon Street, but I never got to do that.
Did you go to Austin ever?
Yeah, yeah, went to, I actually didn't go to the game.
I don't think we had tickets.
Were there any games that were particularly memorable for you?
Oh, that either my freshman or sophomore year was the first time that we had beat Texas in a long, like 20 to 10, long, long time.
And I just remember, Ed Simonini played that game, and I just remember sitting in the stadium after the game, just kind of wondrous, because I realized what a big deal that was.
And looking at the scoreboard, and that was, that probably made more of an impression on me than anything.
What did you and your friends think about Y'all Eaters?
Oh, they were cool.
They were it.
They were the most popular guys on campus.
And if you had a date with a yell leader, you were just hot stuff, and that's all there was to it.
Now, if you had a date with a yell leader, you sat down then on the first row?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And they, after a touchdown, did they run over and kiss the head?
Yes.
Yes.
Okay.
And was there any thought, did you ever hear of any female even dare think about running for yell leader?
No.
No.
Were there, were all the Yell leaders in the Corps then?

Yes, but there was a, Frank Shannon got elected and he was, I don't know if he was the first non-reg Yell leader, but I remember he was a non-reg and that was a big deal when he got, when he got elected.
What about basketball games?
Basketball games were fun.
I didn't go to a whole lot of them.
I just wasn't a big basketball fan and

But one of the gals that I ran around with had a crush on one of the basketball players, so she dragged us along because she didn't want to miss the games and didn't want to go by herself because this guy had no idea who she was.
But they were fun.
G. Raleigh was those old wooden seats.
We packed it.
Nobody goes now.
Isn't that something?
Reed is empty, empty, empty.
And they play this silly, goofy, wild music that has nothing to do with A&M's traditions.
You know, it's fun because baseball now has its own new set of traditions and things that they do at games that are really a lot of fun.
Yes, yes.
And we need to get that for basketball.
And you didn't go to baseball or track or anything.
Let's see, do you remember any concerts or plays, opus?
Oh, I remember a lot of the concerts, town hall concerts before football games.
Seemed like there was always a big concert the Friday night before a football game.
I remember the Ohio players.
I remember Linda Ronstadt.
That was a big deal when Linda Ronstadt came to campus.
Hamilton, Joe Franken, Reynolds, some of the country acts.
But these were all just pop groups that were popular at the time that nobody else has ever heard of.
But I remember just thinking, how did they get these people to come to College Station, Texas?
Did y'all have any hijinks in the dorm?
Any pranks, jokes?
Oh, yeah.
None that I really cared to discuss.
You know, making crank phone calls to guys that you had a crush on.
I remember one night when somebody brought a bunch of cigars and we were all up there smoking cigars.
Oh, God, nasty.
Oh, we've all felt so bad the next day.
Occasionally there were panty raids, but our windows didn't really open, so that was kind of not much of an issue.
But every once in a while some of the guys from Dunn or Ashton would come over and do something crazy.
And there was no streaking during your era, was there?
but I think there were a couple of streaking events like that my first or second year on campus.
I don't remember much about them, but.
What I remember.
What described the Texas A&M's undergraduate student body when you were here?
Where were they from?
Who were they?
What were their basic attitudes, goals?
It was
Well, it was interesting because when I started, fall of 74, my freshman class was the first class that had an approximately equal number of women and men.
So among the freshmen, it looked like what I would imagine that pretty much any other college campus in Texas looked like at the time.
You know, kids in polyester and bell bottoms and,
long hair and, you know, blue eyeshadow, but that kind of describes the college campus now, actually.
But the upperclassmen were very much more male and rural.
And so it was kind of interesting how there was a real dichotomy between the upperclassmen and the underclassmen.
Now, did Krugerdown open that fall?
No, I think it had been open for a year, maybe two.
And so there were, you know, there were a lot of young women on campus and a lot of young women and older men.
Were you all conscious at that time of this being a?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yeah.
It was very, very obvious.
Were you proud to be a part of the transition?
Yeah.
Yeah, I really was.
Really was.
Because we knew that we were the wave of a revolution.
And in family income, generalize about the background of the students.
That was different, too.
I think the younger classmen were more likely to be from upper middle class families in large cities.
